</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/12/a-talk-with-simon-head-author-of-mindless-smarter-machines-are-making-dumber-humans/" data-title="A Talk With Simon Head, Author of &#8216;Mindless: Smarter Machines Are Making Dumber Humans&#8217;" data-description="Mr. Head offers his thoughts on the social landscape of the technology-dominated economy.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/technology/11bits-simonhead/11bits-simonhead-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/technology/11bits-simonhead/11bits-simonhead-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/11/technology/11bits-simonhead/11bits-simonhead-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002820871" width="190" height="244" alt="In his book, &quot;Mindless,&quot; Simon Head Head bemoans a triumph of computer-led systems thinking and so-called âscientific management.â"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="244"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">In his book, "Mindless," Simon Head Head bemoans a triumph of computer-led systems thinking and so-called âscientific management.â</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Simon Head thinks the world has become good for computers, but bad for most humans.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In warehouses run by Amazon and Walmart, he says, workers are monitored by machines, their work output determined by performance optimization programs. At financial institutions like Goldman Sachs, traders and managers depend so heavily on algorithms that they abdicate personal responsibility for events like the subprime mortgage crisis. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The problem isnât just the machines, however; itâs what machines do to thinking. In his <a href="//www.basicbooks.com/full-details?isbn=9780465018444">book</a>, &#8220;Mindless: Why Smarter Machines are Making Dumber Humans,&#8221; Mr. Head bemoans a triumph of computer-led systems thinking and so-called âscientific management.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These have led to âmisindustrialization,â he writes, in which service workersâ emotions are manipulated to optimize retail sales, and Oxford dons are judged by a âresearch excellence frameworkâ that compels them to publish nonsense to meet irrelevant standards.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I recently spoke with Mr. Head about his book, and his thoughts on the social landscape of an economy dominated by technology. This is a condensed and edited version.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <em>Your book flies in the face of more optimistic recent <a href="//www.secondmachineage.com/">work</a> by economists like <a href="//ebusiness.mit.edu/erik/ ">Eric Brynjolfsson</a> and <a href="//andrewmcafee.org/ ">Andrew McAfee</a>. They and others see enormous benefits from spreading information technology widely across society. Why donât you?</em></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Itâs a shame that economists fancy themselves scientists, but they donât deal with history. They donât look at how technology is deployed.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <em>How is technology being deployed?</em></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âProcessâ has become the key word. You hear it all the time from consultancies and systems integrators. What is it? It is the archetypal word from Henry Fordâs system of manufacturing.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <em>But that meant efficiency and uniform yields. Whatâs wrong with that?</em></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> If you mean productivity by itself, perhaps it is successful. In an Amazon warehouse you canât say it is de-skilling people, but it offends the continuum of human dignity to treat people like the appendage of highly efficient machines.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Part of the problem is what has happened to the systems of measurement. The latest in measurement could put sensors on a name tag to monitor how you move, your tone of voice, whether you are conforming to quantitative norms about doing your job. Chairs have sensors to measure your activity at the desk.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <em>How does this trend affect service sector jobs, which have come to dominate the economy?</em></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I have a friend who works in physical rehabilitation at a clinic on Park Avenue. She feels that she needs a minimum of one hour to work with a patient. Recently she was sued for $200,000 by a health insurer, because her feelings exceeded their insurance algorithm. She was taking too long.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The classroom has become a place of scientific management, so that weâve baked the expertise of one expert across many classrooms. Teachers need a particular view. In core services like finance, personnel or education, the variation of cases is so great that you have to allow people individual judgment. My friend canât use her skills.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <em>In perhaps a dark way, wonât this be resolved by more robots doing the repetitive work, freeing people up to do work people are good at?</em></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> That argument has been around a long time. Jobs do arise in areas that people never expected, like personal trainers, personal shoppers or other concierge services. But the economy weâre in now is bringing about the stagnation of most peopleâs incomes. How will they afford concierge services?</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> <em>Is there anything that government can do to help this?</em></p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The system has enormous forces driving it. The single most important thing government can do is the kind of thing you see in Germany, where they provide skills for people who arenât academics. There is lots of professional training, legally mandated skills training on the job. Itâs why Germany has such a great engineering economy, and high incomes. If you invest a lot of money in training people, you wonât fire them. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some companies in the U.S., like Lincoln Electric, or the John Lewis Partnership in the U.K. do a good job of building employee-friendly companies. You can break down the ghettoization of the Walmart economy, but in the U.S. and the U.K., the government has been abysmal.</p>
	</div>
